        "title": "Python White Space Discussion",
        "story": [
          {
            "type": "html",
            "text": "By watching this discussion I had a feeling that both camps (C++ vs Python) are concerned only about safety. That Python significant spacing was made just to type safer and more readable code than C/C++. Well, if that's really the main issue, then answer is self-evident: use both brackets AND significant spacing. Safety is usually implemented through redundancy.",
            "id": "9bad093132901d9ba101bdca8d2c05b7"
          },
          {
            "type": "html",
            "text": "\nUsing both techniques would enable parser to detect cases where you indented a block of code, but forgot brackets. That would be an error. Or a case where you used brackets, but without proper indentation. That would be a warning. Would this increase noise? Well, if a function has 200 characters, adding brackets would result in 202 characters. So we get a huge increase in safety, with only 1% increase in size. Sounds like a good deal to me.",
            "id": "d2dfc10090f5ec823288ac286c39aa6a"
          },
          {
            "type": "html",
            "text": "\nHowever, the problem is not in safety. The problem is that someone don't want to type brackets. While the others are afraid of making a mistake by typing the wrong number of tabs/spaces. If an average person has to choose between the lazy approach and safe approach, the lazy approach usually wins.",
            "id": "e495c5e6d2344d880452951c3ca8b36a"
          },
          {
            "type": "html",
            "text": "\nIf I'm wrong, if the main concern is really about safety, then language should enforce using BOTH. Additionally, such a solution would equally satisfy (or equally annoy) both programming camps.",
            "id": "f428237e2faac16d5c1ca09e9e2df3eb"
          },
          {
